    dek: `The best phone for filmmaking is almost always the one you already own. But there are a few real differences between models that change what you can do — and a handful of setup decisions that matter far more than the badge on the back. Here's how to pick, and how to get the phone ready before you shoot a single frame.`,
    seoTitle: "Choosing Your Phone for Filmmaking: Best Phone & Setup | Filmmaker Genius",
    seoDesc: "Which phone should you shoot on, and what setup matters before you roll? A working filmmaker on picking a phone for filmmaking — storage, battery, model features — without overspending. Chapter 2 of Mobile Filmmaking.",
    body: `<p>Every few months a new phone launches and the internet insists it changes everything for filmmakers. It rarely does. The image quality gap between a current flagship and one from two or three years ago is real but small, and it lives almost entirely in low light and in the newest recording formats. For most of what you'll shoot — a scene with decent light, on a tripod or gimbal, graded with care — a phone that's a couple of generations old will hold up completely. So before you spend money chasing the newest body, understand what actually separates a "filmmaking" phone from a regular one.</p>

<h2>What actually matters when you pick</h2>

<p>If you're choosing between phones, or deciding whether to upgrade, these are the features that genuinely affect your footage — roughly in order of importance:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>A log or flat profile.</b> The single biggest one. A phone that records log (ProRes Log on recent iPhones, or a flat profile on high-end Android) gives you a gradeable image with far more latitude. This is what "cinematic" is built on.</li>
  <li><b>ProRes / high-bitrate codecs.</b> Recording in a less-compressed format holds up much better in the grade than standard highly-compressed video. It eats storage, but the quality difference is visible.</li>
  <li><b>Storage capacity.</b> ProRes and log footage are huge — think gigabytes per minute. Get the largest storage you can, and plan to offload constantly. Running out mid-shoot is a real, avoidable disaster.</li>
  <li><b>Multiple rear lenses.</b> A phone with wide, ultra-wide, and telephoto lenses gives you real focal-length options — closer to having a lens kit than a single fixed view.</li>
  <li><b>Manual control support.</b> Any modern phone can be driven by a pro camera app (Chapter 10), but check that the model plays well with the app you plan to use.</li>
</ul>

<p>Notice what's <em>not</em> on that list: megapixel counts, marketing zoom numbers, and the specific model year. Those sell phones; they don't make your film look better.</p>

<h2>Set it up before you shoot</h2>

<p>Once you've got your phone, spend fifteen minutes getting it shoot-ready — this saves ruined takes later. First, <strong>free up storage and turn on the highest-quality format</strong> you plan to use, then confirm you actually have room for the length of your shoot. Second, put the phone in <strong>Airplane Mode or Do Not Disturb</strong> every single time you roll — there is nothing worse than a perfect take killed by an incoming call or a banner notification lighting up mid-shot. Third, <strong>lock your orientation and clean the lens</strong>: a smudged lens is the number-one cause of mysteriously soft, hazy phone footage, so wipe it with a microfiber cloth before every setup. Fourth, sort out <strong>power and heat</strong> — recording high-quality video drains the battery fast and heats the phone up, which can throttle it or stop recording entirely, so carry a battery pack, keep it out of direct sun, and let it cool between long takes. None of this is glamorous, but a phone that's full, buzzing with notifications, overheating, and shooting a smudged lens will sink a shoot faster than any camera limitation. Get the housekeeping right and the phone becomes a dependable tool you stop thinking about — which is exactly what you want a camera to be.</p>

<div class="pullquote">The best phone for filmmaking is almost always the one you already own. Log recording, storage, and good housekeeping matter far more than the model year.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>My rule before any phone shoot: full battery, empty storage, airplane mode, clean lens. I say it out loud like a pre-flight checklist because I've been burned by every single one of them. The worst was a beautiful golden-hour take, actor nailed it, and the phone had quietly stopped recording thirty seconds in because storage filled up. Cameras don't forgive that, and neither does the light — you don't get golden hour back. Ten minutes of setup buys you a shoot where the gear is the last thing you're worried about.</p>
</div>`,
