    time: "8 min",
    moduleKey: "foundations",
    kicker: "Foundations",
    dek: `Most of what makes phone footage look "like video" comes down to a few default settings the phone gets wrong for film. Fix the frame rate, the shutter, and how you handle exposure and focus, and the same phone suddenly looks like a movie. Here are the settings that matter and the ones that don't.`,
    seoTitle: "Cinematic Mode & iPhone Camera Settings for Filmmaking | Filmmaker Genius",
    seoDesc: "The camera settings that make phone footage look cinematic — resolution, 24fps, shutter speed, cinematic mode, and why locking exposure and focus matters. A working filmmaker's guide. Chapter 3 of Mobile Filmmaking.",
    body: `<p>First, a clarification, because the names confuse everyone. On an iPhone, "<strong>Cinematic mode</strong>" is a specific feature that fakes shallow depth of field and rack focus — it blurs the background artificially. It can look lovely and it can look like a video game, depending on the shot, and it's a creative choice, not the thing that makes footage cinematic. The <em>settings</em> that actually give footage a filmic feel are frame rate, shutter speed, resolution, and exposure — and those apply to any phone, iPhone or Android. Don't confuse the marketing feature with the fundamentals. This chapter is about the fundamentals.</p>

<h2>The settings that give footage a filmic feel</h2>

<p>Get these right and you've done most of the work before you've even framed a shot:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>Shoot 4K at 24fps.</b> 24 frames per second is the frame rate of cinema — it carries the motion cadence your eye reads as "film." 30fps looks like local news; 60fps looks like a soap opera or a phone video. Choose 24 unless you specifically need slow motion.</li>
  <li><b>Set shutter to double your frame rate.</b> The "180-degree rule": at 24fps, aim for a 1/48 or 1/50 shutter. This gives natural motion blur. Too fast a shutter makes movement look stuttery and hyper-real — a dead giveaway of amateur footage. (You'll need a pro app, Chapter 10, to set this manually.)</li>
  <li><b>Lock exposure — don't let it hunt.</b> The phone's auto-exposure constantly re-adjusts as things move, making brightness pulse mid-shot. Tap and hold to lock exposure (AE/AF lock) so a take stays consistent.</li>
  <li><b>Lock focus, too.</b> Autofocus loves to "breathe" — racking in and out looking for a subject. Lock it on your subject so it stays put, and only pull focus deliberately.</li>
  <li><b>Turn slightly under, not over.</b> It's easier to recover shadow detail than to rebuild a blown-out sky. When in doubt, protect your highlights and expose a touch darker.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Frame rate is the one people get wrong</h2>

<p>If you change one thing today, change your frame rate to 24fps and never let the phone default you back to 30 or 60. This single setting is the difference between footage that feels like a film and footage that feels like a clip someone shot at a birthday party — and it's invisible to most beginners because the phone quietly ships at 30fps and nobody tells them otherwise. The reason is physiological: for a century, movies have run at 24 frames a second, so your brain has learned to read that specific slightly-stuttery cadence as "cinema." Higher frame rates look hyper-smooth and hyper-real, which is exactly the "cheap video" look you're trying to escape. The only time to break the 24fps rule is when you <em>want</em> slow motion — then you shoot at a high frame rate (60, 120, 240) specifically so you can slow it down to 24 in the edit, which stretches the motion smoothly. But that's a deliberate effect for a specific shot, not your default. Lock in 24fps for normal shooting, pair it with a 1/48 shutter for natural motion blur, and lock your exposure and focus so nothing pulses or hunts mid-take. That combination — 24fps, 180-degree shutter, locked exposure and focus — is the technical spine of the cinematic look. Everything else is lighting, lenses, and taste.</p>

<div class="pullquote">Shoot 4K at 24 frames a second with a 1/48 shutter, and lock your exposure and focus. That combination is the technical spine of the cinematic look.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>The fastest way to spot a beginner's phone film is motion that looks too smooth and exposure that pulses when someone walks past a window. Both are default settings, not the camera's fault. I set 24fps and lock exposure before I frame anything — it's muscle memory now. The first time you shoot the same location at 30fps auto and then at 24fps locked, side by side, you'll never go back. It's the cheapest upgrade in filmmaking: it costs nothing and it's the biggest single jump toward looking professional.</p>
</div>`,
