    time: "8 min",
    moduleKey: "core",
    kicker: "Core Craft",
    dek: `A phone is a slippery little rectangle designed to be held, not filmed with. A rig turns it into something you can operate like a real camera — mount a lens, attach a mic, hold it steady, run it all day. Here's what actually belongs on your rig, in priority order, and what's just spending money to feel professional.`,
    seoTitle: "iPhone Filming Rig & Essential Accessories for Filmmaking | Filmmaker Genius",
    seoDesc: "What goes in an iPhone filming rig and which accessories actually matter — cages, cold shoes, batteries, and what to skip to save money. A working filmmaker's gear guide. Chapter 5 of Mobile Filmmaking.",
    body: `<p>The word "rig" sounds expensive and intimidating, but at its core a phone rig is just a <strong>cage</strong> — a metal or plastic frame that clamps around your phone and gives it threaded mounting points and cold-shoe slots. That's it. Once your phone lives in a cage, it stops being a phone you're awkwardly balancing and becomes a modular camera you can build onto: a handle here, a mic there, a lens up front. Everything else in this chapter hangs off that one idea. And crucially, you build the rig up <em>only as far as the shot needs</em> — a locked-off tripod shot needs almost nothing on the cage, while a run-and-gun handheld shot needs handles and balance. More metal is not more cinematic. It's just heavier.</p>

<h2>What actually belongs on the rig</h2>

<p>In rough priority order — buy from the top, and stop when your shots stop needing more:</p>

<ul class="spec-list">
  <li><b>A phone cage.</b> The foundation. Gives you 1/4"-20 threads, cold shoes, and a solid grip. Everything else attaches to it. This is the one non-negotiable purchase.</li>
  <li><b>A way to hold it steady.</b> A tripod for locked shots, and/or handles for handheld. Stability is the most visible upgrade you can make — see Chapter 7 for gimbals and movement.</li>
  <li><b>A microphone + mount.</b> A small mic on the cold shoe, or a lav plugged in. Sound is half your film (Chapter 8), and the cage is where the mic lives.</li>
  <li><b>Power.</b> A small power bank velcroed to the rig or in your pocket, feeding the phone as it records. High-quality video drains batteries fast; external power keeps you shooting.</li>
  <li><b>A lens mount or adapter</b> if you're using add-on lenses (Chapter 6). Many cages accept a clamp-on lens or a dedicated lens back.</li>
  <li><b>Optional: an external monitor or a second phone</b> as a bigger viewfinder, and ND filters to control exposure in bright light. Nice, not essential.</li>
</ul>

<h2>Spend on what touches the image</h2>

<p>Here's the rule that'll save you the most money: spend on the things that change what ends up on screen, and go cheap or skip the things that don't. A good lens, a real microphone, and something that keeps the camera steady all directly, visibly change your footage — that's where your money belongs. A carbon-fiber cage instead of an aluminum one, a fancier handle, a matte box on a phone: these make the rig <em>look</em> more like a movie camera without making the <em>image</em> look any better. It's a genuine trap, because a fully built-out phone rig looks incredibly cool and professional, and it's easy to convince yourself the gear is the filmmaking. It isn't. I've seen gorgeous films shot on a phone in a twenty-dollar cage with a good mic and a window for light, and I've seen flat, lifeless footage come off a five-hundred-dollar rig that had everything except a reason for the shot to exist. Build the smallest rig that does the job in front of you, put the saved money into a lens and a mic, and put the saved <em>weight</em> into being able to move quickly. A light, purposeful rig you can actually run with beats a maxed-out one that pins you to a tripod because it's too heavy to handhold. The rig serves the shot — never the other way around.</p>

<div class="pullquote">Spend on the things that change what ends up on screen — a lens, a mic, stability — and skip the metal that only makes the rig look like a movie camera.</div>

<div class="callout">
  <div class="callout-label">◆ From the set</div>
  <p>My travel kit is embarrassingly small: a cage, a clamp-on anamorphic lens, a little shotgun mic, a power bank, and a phone tripod that folds to nothing. It fits in a jacket pocket and it's shot things people assumed came off a cinema camera. Every time I've been tempted to buy more rig, I've asked one question — "will this change the image, or just the photo of me holding it?" If it's the second one, I don't buy it. Keep the rig honest and put the money where the audience can see it.</p>
</div>`,
